Connect the MiniCommand to your computer by connecting both the MIDI IN (the leftmost connector) and the MIDI OUT (the middle connector). Select the patch you want to upload, and press Send Patch. Select the interface to which your MiniCommand is connected, and press \'93Send\'94. Sometimes, refreshing the MIDI ports takes a while, so wait for about 30 seconds if your interface doesn\'92t show up (on MacOSX, this can be \'93fixed\'94 by deleting unused MIDI devices from the \'93Audio Midi Setup\'94 utility). The MiniCommand will switch into the bootloader mode (displaying \'93BOOTLOADER\'94 on its display), and the firmware will be uploaded over sysex. As MIDI is quite slow, this can take up to a minute. If the MiniCommand doesn\'92t switch to the bootloader mode automatically, it can be forced into bootloader mode by holding the topright button down while switching the device on.\
\

\b The Mididuino Editor\

\b0 The Mididuino editor is a modified version of the Arduino editor used to develop firmwares for the Minicommand. It can be downloaded from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://ruinwesen.com/minicommand"}}{\fldrslt http://ruinwesen.com/minicommand}} , the current version that is described in this document is \'93mididuino 018\'94. It comes with the current development version of the Mididuino framework. To get started with the Mididuino, you need to select the correct development board in the Tools menu. The board for the Minicommand is called \'93Minicommand2\'94. Connect the Minicommand to your computer by connecting both the MIDI IN and the MIDI OUT port. Then, select the correct ports in the Tools menu of the Mididuino editor.\
